<div id="review_3727000004" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3727000004" />
    <a title="Steve R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r"><img alt="Steve R" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550608435p2/51602729.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3727000004?book_show_action=true">Dec 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve R" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r">Steve R</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3727000004" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13230363847901002060">I read this book forty-five years ago as part of my penchant for medieval or early modern literature.<br/>Written at almost exactly the same time as Machiavelli&apos;s <i>The Prince</i> in the early part of the sixteenth century, this does for court manners what the other work tried to do for political practice: provide a compendium guide of how to do it properly. The life of these courts of the small, independent, almost always troubled and unsettled Italian city states during the time of the Renaissance was tr</span>
  <span id="freeText13230363847901002060" style="display:none">I read this book forty-five years ago as part of my penchant for medieval or early modern literature.<br />Written at almost exactly the same time as Machiavelli's <i>The Prince</i> in the early part of the sixteenth century, this does for court manners what the other work tried to do for political practice: provide a compendium guide of how to do it properly. The life of these courts of the small, independent, almost always troubled and unsettled Italian city states during the time of the Renaissance was truly very interesting in intellectual, social, moral, political and cultural ways. In this work, questions of etiquette, self-presentation and moral righteousness abound, as does a heartfelt sense of devotion to one Elizabeta Gonzaga, a Duchess whom the author admired, in true courtly-love fashion, from afar. Costing me $2.45, this book has remained on a shelf of my book case for medieval works for almost a half century now.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13230363847901002060" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

